T (Classen's B), in the Laurentian library at Florence. Collated first by Lagomarsini, 1748. Niebuhr pointed out to Classen the importance of its variations from the Vulgate, and this led the latter to make in- ’ quiries leading to the discovery of Ms. from which it differs for the worse in flaws and omissions.

P (Classen’s C), the Turin palimpsest, was discovered by Peyron in the Royal Library at Turin, superscribed with a work of St. Augustine. It consists of 56 leaves of parchment, and contains fragments of ten speeches and of the Ep. ad Fam. Twelve of these leaves belong to the Cluentiana.
